commits.commitMessage:
Increase the socket memory pool size

The current socket memory pool only supports two sockets. However, each
FTP session requires two sockets: one for control commands, and one for
data. That's why when we establish two FTP sessions (two control
sockets), the memory pool has no room for allocating any data socket,
which is used to send/receive data.

Since we need to support 6 FTP sessions, and each FTP session requires
two sockets, we have to enlarge the socket memory pool to support 12
sockets.

Resolves: ATSWI-196
Change-Id: Ic39bb58c082d9cb487556ad17d876b97fb90fa28
commits.subject: Increase the socket memory pool size

commits.commitMessage:
[ALT1250-3446] Continuous of KUDPCFG may cause no response of any commands after

When mutliple AT commands are issued simulatenously, the variable
isAtCmdProcessingPtr is overwritten to false due to which the
semaphore is not released in the AtSwitchCallback and blocks AT port.
Update the variable isAtCmdProcessingPtr to false before releasing
the semaphore.

Resolves: ALT1250-3446
Change-Id: I6560e11d9d8348d271fe8b56376d8cbee4c8f9d3
Signed-off-by: sbalakrishna <sbalakrishna@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [ALT1250-3446] Continuous of KUDPCFG may cause no response of any commands after

commits.commitMessage:
Add hl7800 & hl7802 build mode support

Eurythmics will require to build hl7800 & hl7802 variants
based on the same source code, add this possibility

Resolves: ALT1250-2481
Change-Id: Id1e8705959116aa80e10b712b56bf8b877302aa9
commits.subject: Add hl7800 & hl7802 build mode support

comments.message: Alternately, we could eliminate hl78 target then just use $(MAKECMDGOALS) instead of $(MAP_TARGET).  What's the difference between HL7800 and HL7802?  Should run-test also be modified to be able to build different test for each platform?  Do we need a different .sdef?  Currently PRODUCT_NAME is hl78 (see above).  Should we have different PRODUCT_NAME for hl7800 & hl7802?

HL7800 & HL7802 are not using the same flash mapping, modem images (4g for hl7800, 4g/2g for hl7802) & some configurations. source code is the same, sdef will be the same, so tests should be the same for both platforms at least at start.
Not sure about this project, but overall this commit message format is deprecated.

Can you add some indent with spaces?

Something like:

ifeq ($(filter $(MAKECMDGOALS),hl7800),hl7800)
  MAP_TARGET=hl7800
else ifeq ($(filter $(MAKECMDGOALS),hl7802),hl7802)
  MAP_TARGET=hl7802
else
  MAP_TARGET=all
endif

commits.commitMessage:
Manage le_atServer_SendIntermediateResponse() error case

On Altair1250 platform:
If not enougth place is availble in the output AT response buffer,
le_atServer_SendFinalResponsele_atServer_SendIntermediateResponse
overwrite data and returns LE_FAULT.

On Altair1250 platform:
If not enougth place is availble in the output AT response buffer,
le_atServer_SendFinalResponse() and le_atServer_SendFinalResultCode()
overwrite data ( A OK final response replace is replaced by an ERROR
response in this case) and returns LE_FAULT.

Resolves: LE-10345 LE-10779
Change-Id: I6c2db10ceed13db63456a30699ba3c1405669358
commits.subject: Manage le_atServer_SendIntermediateResponse() error case

comments.message:
This is executed also for sending the final rsp. If app sends "
OK
", we should replace it by "
ERROR
" to inform the error to the host

It is dangerous to replace the final response.
We don't know if it is a intermediate response or a final response
The pattern received is ""%s\r\n" for a intermediate response or the final response.

The success final response is always "\r\nOK\r\n". Only this one has to be replaced.

Discussing with Frederic Dur, we both agree that:
- we mustn't send OK if we truncate the buffer
- so, if "\r\nOK\r\n" is received, we consider it is the final response, and we change it by "+CME ERROR: 20" (means memory full), or "ERROR" (to be 2xcheck if we have access to the extended code value here)
- an error has to be sent to the app through le_atServer_SendFinalResultCode()
- this has to be documented
This is not really true, as we overwrite the buffer (and so we really write count bytes). Maybe better to return -1

why testing atServerSemRef that you don't use later?
you can directly test isAtCmdProcessingPtr
A protection in case atServer_GetSemStatus() can't get the value
useless since either atServer_GetSemStatus has set it either you set it to defaultFalse
A protection in case atServer_GetSemStatus() can't get the value
what about defining the strings directly in const char, instead of #define ?

In patch 4, I proposed +CME ERROR: 20 or ERROR, depending on the extended code value. But it looks we don't have access to that configuration here, so it is fine to go with ERROR only (but to be documented)
It is done in the platform constraint

commits.commitMessage:
Eliminate packageDownloader store thread

The packageDownloader has a store thread which just opens a pipe and
then passes it off to le_fwupdate_Download().  Eliminate this thread
by adding a new function le_fwupdate_DownloadAsync() which performs
the download asynchronously.

Resolves: LE-10714
Change-Id: I2c3195c2219043876d393ddf435e68e3a815b7a2
commits.subject: Eliminate packageDownloader store thread

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

We have to manage the timeout on Legato side

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> We have to manage the timeout on Legato side

Given the APIs provided to us by Altair, this is completely impossible.  The only options are:

- Get Altair to fix AtCmdSendWithTimeout()
- Use AtCmdSend() instead

We could add a watchdog timer, but this should be on a system level, not here.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Looks like atCmdSend() is already in use for commands sent through FAST UART interface.
This should have no negative impact if that is the case, looks good to me then.
Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 1ca7fc43d46acbd6f173b4e06b8112330ab19bf3 by Tristan Pensel

commits.commitMessage:
Improve ATO<Session ID> registrations

Due to Altair AT parser, we must register each ATO<sessionId> commands.
The registration was done MAX_SESSION_ID (10) time in atswi sessionMngr.c
calling Legato atServerUtil_InstallCmdHandler(). This mechanism had effect
of using 10 AT commands pools.
The improvement consist of calling atServerUtil_InstallCmdHandler() only
one time in atswi for ATO. The registration of each the ATO<session ID> will be
handled by le_server_alt1250.c

Resolves: LE-11158
Change-Id: I9edf5281df77f60b8de1ce8864a4ee0f461ddcc2
commits.subject: Improve ATO<Session ID> registrations

commits.commitMessage:
Revise rules for creating AirVantage packages

The old method of creating packages for AirVantage no longer
works as all update packages must now use delta updates.
Create a new set of rules for creating delta update packages
based on instructions provided by product team.

These rules are as follows:

 - make package SWI_FIX=<string>: Create a build package named
   THL78XX.<version>.<SWI_FIX>.exe.  Numeric SWI_FIX versions
   are reserved for Dizzy integration.
 - make delta-update \
       OLD_PACKAGE=<PACKAGE_NAME> [NEW_PACKAGE=<PACKAGE_NAME>]:
   Create a delta-update between OLD_PACKAGE and NEW_PACKAGE.
   If no NEW_PACKAGE is provided, the current build is used.

Additionally make distclean has been modified to delete all
packages and delta updates.

Resolves: LE-11044
Change-Id: I33577ae58009266dde698d87afb297c385051da4

Patch Set 1:

Need to choose between this and (https://gerrit-legato/q/topic:%22rtos-LE-10714-eliminate-store-thread%22+(status:open%20OR%20status:merged)), as [async] and [direct] are incompatible.

Do we need to add locking to le_fwupdate_...() APIs?  [direct] doesn't do any synchronization.

Patch Set 1:

In my opinion, we could go with this first, and replace by LE-10714 when it is ready: the very advantage of LE-10714 is to remove the donwload thread from AVC, and so simplify the design and the code.

Regarding the lock, yes, we should do. But:
- in this system, fwupdate has one client
- fwupdate APIs calls take a long time, and AVC design has been done to not stay locked during these calls. So I believe we don't have simultaneous APIs calls.

Anyway, adding a mutex in the pa_fwupdate is certainly more secure than this assumption.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Okay, that makes sense to me - go with this initially and add the lock then.

commits.commitMessage:
Move AtServer related device implementation into atServer.

Previously AtServer-related devices were implemented in the Legato
framework, requiring a backward dependency of framework on AtServer.
With the fd rework, these can now be moved up to AtServer.

Resolves: LE-10393
Change-Id: Ibae8f6ee9b144a59a57c0e12080b8fc8ff4b5fbd
commits.subject: Move AtServer related device implementation into atServer.

comments.message: This feels a little fragile to me, but I guess it's okay as long as AtDevices is guaranteed to have paired entries, and the pairs are always in the right sequence.
Probably clearer if this was just -1.
This is where OpenBSD's strlcat() is nice :P.
add a note to explain that atServer and dataPort must be interleaved.
add a comment to explain that it is linked to the organization of AtDevice
Probably.  But this still works if MAX_DEVICE_NUM ever becomes bigger, and I've spent enough time chasing off-by-one errors I'd rather give myself a more space.

If we want to be very rigorous, all the data functions shouldn't be put in that file, as they no relate to the AT commands word.

But it is better here than in fa_fd.c anyway, and not sure if we have a better place to put it
Why calling this in this init COMPONENT_INIT_ONCE function, instead of COMPONENT_INIT ? (2 init functions add complexity IMO)

Honestly I can't remember off the top of my head.  But COMPONENT_INIT_ONCE is called earlier than COMPONENT_INIT, so will be called before other component's COMPONENT_INIT are called.  So I think these devices need to be created before other COMPONENT_INIT() functions are run.

commits.commitMessage:
Remove incorrect linker flags

Linker flags are global on RTOS, so should not be present in cdefs
except for libraries and library paths.

Here "-s" strips unneeded symbols (including debug information) which
prevents debugging on RTOS; -Bsymbolic affects shared library linking,
but RTOS does not build a shared library; and -gc-sections is supplied
by mkTools when needed so should not be included here.

Resolves: LE-10770
Change-Id: Ibfe86411afce97e5b3c291aa7aedceaf420f8536
commits.subject: Remove incorrect linker flags

commits.commitMessage:
Add AV_SYSTEM_CONFIGURATION compilation flag

Add a flag for AirVantage FW version use case for HL78 product

Resolves: LE-10578
Change-Id: If1b8bc5dc1c5fadec6f6c8e63ded13bdc5fa368d
commits.subject: Add AV_SYSTEM_CONFIGURATION compilation flag

comments.message: What does that mean? It's not really obvious...

System Configuration is the AV term for the other update mechanism than bundle
The difference in device isde between system configuration and bundle is only the FW version string format
I wanted to support both format
If SYSTEM_CONFIGURATION flag is embedded, the FW version format is for system config
If it's not embedded, the FW version format is for the bundle mechanism
to avoid any confusion I suggest AV_SYSTEM_CONFIGURATION

commits.commitMessage:
Enable gcc optimization flag in debug build

Debug builds are currently done without any GCC optimization, which
unfortunately causes some timing issues at runtime on RTOS (preventing
usage of debug logs and AVC dtls connection for instance).
As a tradeoff, this enables GCC optimization flag -0s in debug builds
to allow usage of debug logs without hindering AVC connectivity.

Resolves: LE-XXXX
Change-Id: I53864847d95c7cbe326e93902b35e7f6ad5ac14c
commits.subject: Enable gcc optimization flag in debug build

comments.message: Should this always be sent to the last port?

I think this is used throughout our code when you do not care about the logical port - that is, not every function invoked by AtCmdSendWithTimeout() makes use of logical port id. LOGICAL_SERIAL_ID_MAX is our way of specifying "do not care"
Better to have a function which returns directly the fd, instead of calling le_fd_Open() below

I do not think we can bypass le_fd_Open(). Lots of things happen there (reference count increment which is decremented in the subsequent "close" calls, also, take a look at AtServerOpen()/DataPortOpen). So, bottom line - le_fd_Open() must be called, the way it is right now

Sorry for the late review first of all, should have chimed in earlier on this.

le_fd service was thought as a posix substitute, an abstraction to interact with devices by mimicking some of the posix apis where we see fit. It may be seen as a matter of taste but this looks out of place to me in that general picture :).
Here's a suggestion: why not plug the functionality of le_fd_DeviceNameFromLogicalPort() directly into le_fd_Open() ? More precisely, I'm thinking about something like:

le_fd_Open("logicalPort", (int)logicalPort);

Then you could just do the same processing as le_fd_DeviceNameFromLogicalPort(), only based on the device name "logicalPort" (feel free to choose a more fitting device name by the way).

What do you think ?

Please do not mind my previous comment, your initial approach to add an le_fd_DeviceNameFromLogicalPort() function is the better one.

Here's a few suggestions:

- since the underlying AT device has already been opened by portService, there should not be any call to le_fd_Open() in AtSwitchCallback(): the idea is to use your function to translate the logicalPort id directly into the underlying device fd, and use that fd when calling fdMon_GetFdMonitorRef() below (as a consequence this will indeed remove the call to le_fd_Open() below),

- since your translation function is a contraption specific to the case of AtSwitchCallback(), it may well be treated as an internal function not exposed in the le_fd interface: instead of declaring it in le_fd.h, you could add it to some le_fd_local.h file in frameworkAdaptor/ so that it stays specific to HL78 (this will allow us not to worry about it when le_fd code is ported back to Legato master branch).

commits.commitMessage:
Ensure AT client commands are properly terminated

Many of the AT command handlers in the Legato and MAP code expect AT
commands to be terminated with at least one of a newline or carriage
return.

This patch also adds a make target to build an HL78 bundle for AVC.
The default name field in the package can be overridden by setting the
PKG_NAME environment variable.

Resolves: LE-10311 LE-10313 LE-10314
Change-Id: I09e184b923b12fa3d216b71cb9d422e52d212cae
commits.subject: Ensure AT client commands are properly terminated

commits.commitMessage:
Resolve AT parser issue for CLI commands

AT commands issued from the CLI were not being terminated with a
carriage return (0x0D), and so were causing the parser to hang,
thinking that more input was expected.

This patch ensures that all AT commands are properly terminated.

Resolves: LE-10281
Change-Id: I81c620242770126f37de518a57c4cddda1f8af2f
commits.subject: Resolve AT parser issue for CLI commands

commits.commitMessage:
Integrate packageDownloader instead of curl library

Due to memory consumption concerns and unresolved issues related to
curl integration on RTOS, the library is being replaced by a custom
package download for AirVantageConnector component.
This patch integrates the work-in-progress packageDownloader instead
of curl library.

Resolves: LE-9894
Change-Id: If0f677d946e94dd9c6342d9d755798870963b810
commits.subject: Integrate packageDownloader instead of curl library

Use MAP API to Get/Set/Delete credential

Use MAP APIs to manage credentials on ALT1250 platform
lwm2mcore_GetCredential(), lwm2mcore_SetCredential(),
lwm2mcore_DeleteCredential(), lwm2mcore_CheckCredential().

lwm2mcore_SetCredential() can't create a new entry.

Resolves: LE-10060
Change-Id: Id05bab6b995382f8888896f454caa3537b7da727
commits.subject: Use MAP API to Get/Set/Delete credential

comments.message: Add a comment saying that this implementation is ALT1250-specific.
Can we factorize better the code of osPortCredentials.c to avoid too many copy-paste between the 2 versions of the file?

Need to keep in comment ?
line 32 and line 48

Why don't you manage all?

AVMS.Cred.Firmware_PubKey for Firmware_PubKey
AVMS.Cred.BootstrapServerAddr for BootstrapServerAddr
AVMS.Cred.PSKIdentity for PSKIdentity
AVMS.Cred.PSK for PSK
AVMS.Cred.FWKeyIndex for FWKeyIndex

Prefer alignment like:
    int res = read_encrypted_json_option(CredentialLocations[credId],
                                         AVMSCredentialFolder,
                                         (uint8_t*)bufferPtr, lenPtr);

Check in whole file
Nothing has been planed in this way, but it is a good way.

The name is misleading. The decoded data is supposed to be an array of bytes. If these bytes are actually a string, the decoded data do not have the final 0. So you must be sure to add this 0 if you want to process it like a string (use strlen, etc.)

Perhaps add a test on ptrStr? assert(ptrStr) ?
(even if the read_encrypted_json_option will return an error if ptrStr was not correctly allocated)
In this case the read_encrypted_json_option returns error and the ptrStr is not used.
Caution: as stated above, ptrStr is not a string. So if dataLen == *lenPtr, there will not be a final 0 (otherwise as the array is already filled by 0s, a final 0 will still be there).
it is copied with memcpy() and not strcpy() API.

commits.commitMessage:
Additional AVC integration changes

This patch brings the following changes on top of the initial
AirVantageConnector integration patch:

- disable hasmap naming at build time to free some RAM since related
  build issue was fixed,
- enable dataConnectionService, secStore and fwupdateService automatic
  start at runtime since concurrency issue on services startup didn't
  occur with uLegato 18.02,
- raise avcService stack size from 12KB to 16KB to avoid stack
  overflow issues.

Resolves: LE-9894
Change-Id: Ieabc77002af51e10307f1dae6a638c6d6c791dba
commits.subject: Additional AVC integration changes

Patch Set 1:

Keith, 
This is not a complete copy of le_atClient. The previous implementation was done as generic component le_atClient code + Linux/Altair PAs.

The latest HL78 implementation was done as "ad hoc" HL78. It does not create the thread created in le_atClient_Start(), hence saving the memory on the HL78 side. Also, the generic le_atClient timeout implementation would not work for Altair. Finally, the parsing code is not the same, some cases that are not possible on HL78 platform were removed from the parsing code.

commits.commitMessage:
Implement le_atClient API as library

Implemented le_atClient as library. This was done
to save memory (HL78 le_atClient implementation now does not
create a new thread, unlike the Linux version). Other reasons,
the timeout model implemented in the original le_atClient
(component) would not work for HL78 - timeout must be
"delegated" to Altair code. Also, parsing function was changed to
eliminate cases which are not possible in HL78, but were possible
in Linux (component) implementation.
Renamed atClientAlt1250->atClient

Resolves: LE-9889
Change-Id: I74a7fde84ef905d68ac9f5cfaec6042e9ab3f9a4
commits.subject: Implement le_atClient API as library

It's a pity to disable it because it can be useful but I agree thaht the code is not efficient. I think that a rework based on a linked list could be more efficient by avoiding the long search time of a free slot.

Patch Set 1:

> It's a pity to disable it because it can be useful but I agree
 > thaht the code is not efficient. I think that a rework based on a
 > linked list could be more efficient by avoiding the long search
 > time of a free slot.

I agree linked list would be the correct way to do this.  That would also fix issue of running out of slots.  The other thing that should be disabled (or at least configurable) is how often check is done.  Currently check is done every context switch, which although fine-grained, is horribly inefficient.

commits.commitMessage:
Disable ALTAIR_SUPPORT_PER_TASK_MEM_TRACE

Legato uses too many memory allocations for Altair's memory tracing,
causing superfluous errors even though the underlying malloc()/free()
calls were succeeding.  So disable ALTAIR_SUPPORT_PER_TASK_MEM_TRACE
when compiling Legato.

Resolves: LE-9959
Change-Id: Ib7a0639fc87422db92c9f6074a5669a3a69d12d2
commits.subject: Disable ALTAIR_SUPPORT_PER_TASK_MEM_TRACE

commits.commitMessage:
Implement riPin support in HL78

Implemented support for Ring Indicator PIN in HL78. No platform
adaptor was added. The code directly invokes HL78 gpio service.
Unlike Linux platform HL78 does not have a permanent thread
for RI PIN "service". Instead, thread is created on demand
and destroyed when not needed

Resolves: LE-8186
Change-Id: I2f149767da21fcbc9f5cee2e92052bd925056cc2
commits.subject: Implement riPin support in HL78

comments.message: is it really useful to have a set of functions by gpio ???
no, but it's the current design of this API...

Yeah, Jon & I have had some discussions on how we could "fix" this API.  

Original reason was so Legato could access control on a per-pin basis so (for example) a program designed to control LED couldn't be hacked to trigger reset pin as there would be no binding to reset pin API.  But of course this doesn't apply on RTOS as we currently have no access control at all.

commits.commitMessage:
Update hl78.sdef to support AV

- disable objects naming, except for thread and hashmaps
- disable calls to configTree
- add stubs for tinycbor, gnss and positioning
- adapt tinydtls makefile
- optimize libcurl link (may be useless)
- remove not-applicable 'bundles' section from modemService.adef,
- prevent additional platform services to start automatically to
  mitigate a startup dependency issue between modemService and
  atService (modemService needs to be start first, atService second),
- raise avcDaemon stack size from 4096 to 12288 Bytes to prevent
  "socket creation crashes" symptom,
- do not rely on 3rdParty makefiles that build LwM2M2Core and Wakaama
  as shared libraries.

Resolves: LE-7588
Change-Id: I4a31093a99cf99b6f9dc2428d7ba4fc846afa694
commits.subject: Update hl78.sdef to support AV

commits.commitMessage:
Prevent atSwitch command processing when atServer is suspended

On RTOS, commands received on the AT port are processed by atServer
with a specific callback registered with atSwitch component.
When atServer is suspended atSwitch still calls the callback function
for processing, which results in an error to get a valid fdMonitor
reference and prevent the callback to return properly.
This patch prevents the atSwitch command processing when atServer is
suspended and allows the callback function to return properly.

Resolves: LE-9344
Change-Id: I0e8e6158c6ed9df67aa2345e3bb0a4807bf3ffac
commits.subject: Prevent atSwitch command processing when atServer is suspended

comments.message: Please move all LE_INFO to LE_DEBUG, we must take care of Flash footprint.
You have this code repeated several times, I think it can be factorized with one single function.

Please refer to our coding rules:
http://legato.io/legato-docs/latest/ccodingStdsFormat.html#codingFormatNamingFunctions

In the present case, 'Gpio' prefix is useless for static functions, we know that all of those are about GPIO, so please rename them as follows:
GpioIsOutput -> IsOutput
GpioReadValue -> ReadValue
GpioSetOutputAndValue -> SetOutputAndValue
etc ...

Implement support for GPIO polarity setting

We need to be able to set "polarity" for the
input GPIO pins. Polarity means configuring level (high
or low) at which the GPIO pin is considered 'active'.
The feature is currently applied to input pins.

Resolves: LE-9401

commits.commitMessage:
Turn on GCC size optimization for system

Previously only parts of the binary were optimized for size.  Running
with

    make DEBUG=yes

will turn this optimization off and emit debug code instead.

Turning on -Os reduces the binary size by about 20%.

Resolves: LE-9376
Change-Id: I6820a524abc9a955edf0f2a1b4e7edafa2d81cf8

commits.commitMessage:
Avoid potential partial link issues due to global variables use

In order to avoid potential memory corruption issues due to partial
link issues when usign global variables, this patch declares such
variables as static since they are accessed via getter and setter
functions anyway.
Moreover the use of global variables is not recommended by the coding
style so this should not have been done in the first place.

Resolves: LE-8756
Change-Id: I4d5a7214a1160b98180e88515e8c966ec2182bd5
commits.subject: Avoid potential partial link issues due to global variables use

comments.message: Actually, I think this envVars: section should just be removed entirely.
If you want to use an opaque type, you shouldn't expose the structure definition. The structure definition must remain hidden in the .c file.
Perhaps my information are outdated, but I see that GPIO3 should be available too and not GPIO9 (see AirPrime - HL7800 - Product Technical Specification - Rev1.0.pdf)
we don't need to add a prefix for any objects that are not exposed outside the file

CamelCase

Global var starts with a capital letter
local var start with a lower-case letter

I notice we use more Alt1250 instead of Altair.
Pease change te prefix name to gpioAlt1250_
Since that code is for Alt1250 only, why do you need a flag?
Can you see file gpio_alt1250.c and array io_cfg_sel[] - I think I needed this definition because of that...even though...this (GPIO pin layout) does not match what I observed.

So it's not in the right place.
Here you define your component that only contains gpioService.c, file gpio_alt1250.c is not included here.
If I understand well, I think this cflags must be moved into the .adef.
Tristan, I do not think you can put cflags spec into adef file.
I'd prefer you replace Altair with Alt1250 in your namings
we use prefix only for external declaration. Here, just name it GpioDir_t

You need this if you need to allocate a specific context when an app want to use the GPIO1... Is this the case? I'm not sure.

BTW, I think it's useless in our case, just double check with Keith.
Sorry to bother you with that, but I meant Alt1250, not Altair1250...

commits.commitMessage:
Add "test" and "install" targets to makefile.

- "test" target will build a test system.
- "install" target will install the last built system using Altair flash
  tool.  Use DEST= to set target serial port.  Altair board must be
  in uboot due to limitation in current Altair tool.

Resolves: LE-8390
Change-Id: I3c098df24146ac6217c7691ff60bec0a6b1ffbaf
commits.subject: Add "test" and "install" targets to makefile.

comments.message:
need to be configurable by the user.
I'm downloading at 921600 and some ports are not compliant with 460800

need to be configurable by the user.
I'm downloading at 921600 and some ports are not compliant with 460800

I disagree.  This is an internal project, so we should be going for ease of use over flexibility.  Pick a baud rate which is widely supported, then specify anyone developing for hl78 needs a serial port adapter compatible with that baud rate.

If you want a different baud rate, you can still install manually.

Saying to the people to install manually is not easing their life ;)
I'm thinking to the integration team which have their specific serial adapters to manage lot of devices (one USB port give them several ports) and I'm not sure that they support this speed.
Having a default value is a good thing but perhaps can we define an environment variable to allow the user to overwrite it?

commits.commitMessage:
Switch from $(shell realpath ) to $(abspath) in Makefile

realpath may return an empty string on some systems if path does not exist.
Use abspath instead which doesn't have this behaviour; we don't need
canonicalization provided by realpath.

Resolves: LE-8440
Change-Id: I7d9a8df7d3e4b4a90c0ec85a8a71b00ab3e223d7

commits.commitMessage:
Keep build utilities in path environment variable

Legato relies on the ninja build system utility which executable name
varies depending on the Linux distribution. As a result, Legato
creates a link to the actual ninja executable on the host system as
part as its build utilities.
This patch ensures that the build utilities are kept in the path
envrionment variable by adding them to the toplevel makefile.

Resolves: LE-8178
Change-Id: Ie050b94f4c0e80b332276cc75c75895c586c4c3b
commits.subject: Keep build utilities in path environment variable

comments.message:
This is needed at least for ninja because the tool is not always found by Legato build system on some Linux distributions:
- For Debian based distros ninja executable is called 'ninja', but
- For Red Hat based distros ninja executable is called 'ninja-build'.

We need to always rely on $(LEGATO_ROOT)/bin/ninja which is a link to the actual ninja executable on the host system.

This is needed at least for ninja because the tool is not always found by Legato build system on some Linux distributions:

- For Debian based distros ninja executable is called 'ninja', but
- For Red Hat based distros ninja executable is called 'ninja-build'.

We need to always rely on $(LEGATO_ROOT)/bin/ninja which is a link to the actual ninja executable on the host system.
Ok.  This also fixes problems with ifgen that Vlad has seen.
Since $(LEGATO_ROOT)/bin is being added back to the path, it can be removed from here again.

I would prefer to use a solution that doesn't require another package dependency that isn't normally installed on most development PC Linux distros.

Also, it will be very unintuitive to maintainers to find that rsync is being used for a copy operation.  This should therefore be commented.

Line length.

Also should add -fp flag to cp command.

-f: force i.e. remove before copy if file can't be overwritten.
-p: preserve times so Make gets the right mtime.
Not necessary.  Make commands execute in a subshell.

Complex enough that it needs a comment.
As a general rule, Makefiles and any other build scripts (or any code at all, for that matter) should be commented unless what it is doing is obvious at a glance.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix build dependency on altair config header

Legato framework adaptor sources rely on a config header that is
generated during the configuration step of the Altair build process.
As a consequence, the framework cannot be built before that header is
generated.
This patch fixes the build dependency on that config header by running
the configuration step of the Altair build before building the
framework.

Resolves: LE-8020
Change-Id: If84e0484f3e706e4c2a03900ae0a73b5d84b3e1c
commits.subject: Fix build dependency on altair config header

comments.message: I think you added map configuration as a dependency for liblegato, in which case framework needs to depend on map-config.
This won't work, because KCONFIG_CONFIG variable which is set for the framework breaks the Altair build.
Then Legato should be fixed so there's no conflict.  See https://gerrit-legato/18717.
$(LEGATO_TARGET_LIB) should just depend on map-config instead of duplicating build rules.
If we don't re-run the config after copying liblegato, then Altair build will not pick up the library to link it into the final binary.

comments.message: I think this should be just .config -- if the user specifies a different config via make KCONFIG_CONFIG=my-config.config this makefile should not overwrite their config.
So .config.mk above should depend on .config too, instead of depending on the relative path to the file.

If KCONFIG_CONFIG and .config are different, .config.mk always has to be updated from $(KCONFIG_CONFIG) since Legato uses $(KCONFIG_CONFIG) for generating le_config.h; and .config.mk and le_config.h have to match up.

At least for Legato, the way I see it default.config should only be copied over if KCONFIG_CONFIG has not been overriden by a user or product.  If either *have* set KCONFIG_CONFIG, Legato assumes whoever set KCONFIG_CONFIG set a valid config & they know what they're doing, so never touch it.  Which is why in legato/Makefile it copies over default.config to .config instead of $(KCONFIG_CONFIG) -- this way it will never overwrite (for example) the hl78 config with the Linux default config, if KCONFIG_CONFIG is set to the hl78 config.
So, the only purpose of this is to pass the .config file's path to the Legato AF Makefiles, no?

comments.message: I guess this fetch stuff goes away now, since we're using repo to do the fetching.
Seems to be called just "hl78" everywhere else.
Is there a difference between FreeRTOS and OpenRTOS besides licensing?
In theory there is none (besides licensing), in practice I do not know for sure.
As per discussion with jchitty, include configuration from openrtos map core here in order to have all the KConfig generated stuff at the product level.

As per discussion with jchitty, this goal should not be exposed in the top level makefile: map core already provides a default configuration to allow building without invoking menuconfig. If re-configuration is needed, user should just 'cd' in proper directory and 'make menuconfig' there to update the default config.

Remove this goal.

Sorry, didn't notice this before.

Shouldn't 'all' build the product?  I don't see much need to build the framework by itself from the product level Makefile.

If 'all' builds the product (and is the default), then 'hl78' is really only needed if someone wants to do things the old-fashioned 'make wp85' way.  But the new way we discussed is to just 'make'.

The intention was to be able to build the framework sources separately from openrtos to ease the workflow until we have an executable liblegato to link with (at which stage we could afford to build openrtos binary + libleagto in a single step).

But I guess we already have the "framework" goal for that purpose. Fair enough then, I'll add the instructions to build the product at once.

Done
Shouldn't this use the toolchain gcc?
HL78 toolchain only provides cross compilation tools: for localhost target we still rely on the host gcc.

Unless it's changed in uLegato framework is on-target framework, so should be built with target CC.  On master framework is built with:

    $(MAKE) -f Makefile.framework CC=$(TARGET_CC)

In any event you're also setting TARGET_CC=gcc below; presumably that should at least by cross-compiler.
Does that mean "TARGET=localhost" in the recipe is wrong (knowing that we don't have any other target we can build a functional framework for at the moment) ?

Yes, I think it should be TARGET=hl78 (didn't notice that earlier).  Yes, it won't compile, but that's entirely expected at this point.  But trying to build hl78 gives a point for hl78 porting work to start.

Should this replace buildVars section from .sdef?  If not, what configuration settings get set in Kconfig vs. which get set in .sdef/.sinc?

Can this file be included in .the .sdef/.sinc so there's no change in workflow for users who don't go through our makefiles (e.g. DevStudio)?

We had a discussion about buildVars vs KConfig and the idea was to use KConfig as a more user-friendly way to configure the build environment of a product (ie. use menuconfig to configure all build variables for a specific product through a single tool, instead of going through .sdef/.sinc files scattered around the source code), so I guess it is intended as replacement buildVars in the long run.

The config file is already included in hl78 Makefile, so we should be able to include/source it in a .sdef/.sinc file if needed (granted the name of the env variables and the corresponding paths are correctly set).

That being said, we're also trying KConfig as an experiment on hl78 because Altair's openrtos already rely on KConfig anyway: it should be easier to backtrack if the experiment does not ease the workflow in the end.
Ultimately, yes, I think we should replace the buildVars section with KConfig entries.  But not as part of this change.

I think we need some way to include this file in the .sdef directly, not rely on going through Makefile.  Otherwise there's a regression on LE-4970.

FWIW all configuration is currently in target/${LEGATO_TARGET}.sinc, not scattered throughout the tree.  This change actually scatters configuration IMO as it separates compiler config from other configuration settings (cflags, cxxflags, ldflags are still be in .sinc as far as I can see).
Maybe start with a minimal .sdef based on $LEGATO_ROOT/default.sdef?

There's a lot of services in $LEGATO_ROOT/default.sdef that are not required for hl78.
The goal of this .sdef is to declare only the services that are required by the product.
At the moment you have nothing -- we should know (or be able to figure out) a good idea of what services we will need, so I think we might as well put those in now.  Not a big deal though.

I don't understand what you are asking for here.

The services that will be needed for HL78 are currently being worked on in a QEMU environment (see https://gerrit-legato/#/c/17411/3/modules/HL78xx/hl78virt.sdef).

By just listing them here, none of those currently build successfully for HL78: how do you suggest we fix that ?
Yeah, I think we should add them as we bring them on-line, so to speak.

Now I'm really confused.  Why are we doing hl78virt in a completely separate repo/branch from hl78 & separate build system?  IMO these two should be done side-by-side in the same repo using the same build system.  I would expect both include the same app list via #include.

Anyway my original thought was maybe put them in but commented out (or similar).  Empty .sdef looks a little barren.  Since hl78 will need AVC & AT which are included using .sinc could also test including those .sincs work -- IIRC they need some buildVars set first.

We've tried that and it's what we have today.  We're finding it's not scalable.  We were looking at splitting everything (although looking for commonality that we can share, so it's not a completely separate build system). But, maybe in this case we can combine the virt target and the actual target into one repository+Makefile+manifest combo?  It will mean that any CI system that wants to build it will need to know that it has special make goals, though.

BTW, didn't the 1250 chip QEMU emulation get abandoned by Altair when they got the real thing going?  Someone told me that once.

> But, maybe in this case we can combine the virt target and the actual target into one repository+Makefile+manifest combo?

This is all I was suggesting.  Moot since hl78virt target is temporary & not planned to be merged into master.

Can replace all of this with

 $(MAP_BUILD_DIR):
     mkdir -p $@

Then replace all other occurrences of 'map-build-dir' with '$(MAP_BUILD_DIR)'.

That way, make will check the file system for the directory, and if it's not there will run the 'mkdir -p $@' recipe to create it; but if the directory is already there, make will do nothing.
I think we could simplify even further the 'all' and 'hl78' targets by removing the recipe from the 'hl78' goal and making 'hl78' depend on 'all'.  Then you don't need the 'BUILD-MAP' variable.
There's really no difference between these.  hl78 is just an alias for 'all' (as it should be).
Where does this come from?  I don't seem to have it on my system.
This binary is part of Altair's delivery. It's available in {HL78 ROOT}/map/utils/mconf and must be added to $PATH.

I'm thinking we should add mconf to the tool chain.  It's an integral part of our build system.  Then this line in the Makefile will become unnecessary (should be replaced by a -include toolchain/Makefile.inc or something like that, I think).
